# What systemd is (PID 1)

The **init system** — PID 1 — on every modern distro, plus a suite of daemons (`journald`, `logind`, `resolved`, `timesyncd`). First process the kernel starts, ancestor of all *(module 05)*.

## What it does

- **Starts services in dependency order**, in parallel → fast boots
- **Manages lifecycles** — restart on crash, on schedule, on demand
- **Tracks with cgroups** — stopping a service kills *all* its children
- **Aggregates logs** + **defines boot targets**

## Everything is a unit — location = priority

| Location | What |
|---|---|
| **`/lib/systemd/system/`** | **vendor** units — don't edit |
| **`/etc/systemd/system/`** | **admin** + your own — **edit here** |
| `~/.config/systemd/user/` | per-user |

Rule: **read** in `/lib`, **write** in `/etc` — that's what survives a package update.
